WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-Nuit English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
And I'm Beth. Neil, what type of food do you often eat?

5
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Well, basic things to fill me up that sort of bread potatoes.

6
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Well, food like this, which is regularly eaten by many people, is known as a staple.

7
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
In Britain, bread is a popular staple, but for large parts of the world there's another food which is number one, rice.

8
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
That's right, over half the world's population eats rice as the staple food, especially in Asia.

9
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
But rice is a very thirsty crop, which needs lots of water to grow.

10
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
And this is becoming a problem because of droughts and flooding caused by climate change.

11
00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:01.000
In this program, we'll be hearing about a pioneering new technique helping farmers to grow rice in the face of a changing climate.

12
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
As usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases.

13
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And remember, you can find all the vocabulary from this program on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

14
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.000
But first, I have a question for you, Beth.

15
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Just now, I mentioned that rice is a very thirsty crop.

16
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
So how much water is needed to grow one kilogram of rice?

17
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Is it a, a thousand to three thousand liters?

18
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
B, three thousand to five thousand liters?

19
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Or C, five thousand to seven thousand liters?

20
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
I'm going to say C, five thousand to seven thousand liters.

21
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Well, we'll find out if that's right at the end of the program.

22
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Dr. Ivonne Pinto is director general of the International Rice Research Institute,

23
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
or I, R, R, R, R for short, based in the Philippines.

24
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Here, she explains more about the global popularity of rice to BBC World Service program, The Food Chain.

25
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Between 50 and 56 percent of the world's population rely on rice as the principal staple.

26
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Now, that's roughly about four billion people.

27
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
And it is one of those commodities that is grown really extensively, particularly in South Asia and Southeast Asia,

28
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.000
but increasingly the appetite for it is growing in continents like Africa.

29
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And of course, there are also Latin American and European rice varieties.

30
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Rice is a commodity, a produce that can be bought and sold.

31
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Like other crops, rice has varieties, different types.

32
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
For example, brown rice, long-grain rice, or basmati.

33
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Much of the research into rice today is focused on making new varieties that can adapt to the changing environment,

34
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
and grow in conditions of either too much or too little water.

35
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Over half the world's population eats rice and there's a growing demand in Africa and Europe too.

36
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So clearly, there's an appetite, a strong desire for rice worldwide.

37
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
So is it possible to grow rice in a more eco-friendly way?

38
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Jean-Philippe Blabbard, director of rice company Tilda, thinks the answer lies in a new growing technique called alternate wet drying or a WD for short.

39
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:27.000
To grow rice farmers go through cycles of flooding their fields or paddies, which then dry out and need to be flooded again.

40
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:36.000
With a WD, measuring pipes are placed 15 centimeters underground so that farmers can check water levels at any part of the field.

41
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Normally rice needs 25 cycles of flooding and drying out to grow.

42
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:48.000
But using a WD, this is reduced to 20 cycles, saving farmers water and reducing methane emissions.

43
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.000
His Jean-Philippe Blabbard, telling Grief Alexander, presenter of BBC World Services, the Food Chain,

44
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
how he began his AWD experiment with farmers in India.

45
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:08.000
We've got last year 126.8 farmers on board applying this AWS technique to reduce the overall methane emission.

46
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:11.000
And how did you persuade those farmers to give it a go?

47
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.000
That was quite challenging because, obviously, the main challenge is for farmers the apprehension to lose revenues.

48
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.000
They need to see tangible results at the end of the crop, that they are getting, or, usually, something better.

49
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Many Indian farmers got on board with Jean-Philippe's experiment.

50
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
If you get on board with something, you agree to a plan of action and get involved.

51
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
In other words, you give it a go. You try doing something to see if it works.

52
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:46.000
As it turned out, the new technique produced tangible results, results which are real and measurable.

53
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Using a WD, the amounts of water and electricity needed to grow rice decreased.

54
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Methane gas emissions reduced, and on top of that, the amount of rice yielded increased.

55
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
Right, Neil, isn't it time you revealed the answer to your question?

56
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:09.000
I asked how many liters of water are needed to grow just one kilogram of rice.

57
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:16.000
And the answer was 3,000 to 5,000 liters, so thirsty, but not as thirsty as you thought.

58
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this programme, starting with commodity, a product like rice that can be bought and sold.

59
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Varieties of something are different types of it.

60
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.000
If there's an appetite for something, there's a strong desire or demand for it.

61
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:38.000
If you get on board with an idea or a plan, you agree to do something and get involved with doing it.

62
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
To give it a go means to try doing something.

63
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
And finally, the adjective tangible means real and measurable.

64
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

65
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:55.000
If you've enjoyed this programme, why not try practising the new vocabulary you've learned with our worksheet?

66
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.000
It's available to download now from our website, bbclearningenglish.com.

67
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
And you could also try out the quiz while you're there. Goodbye for now.

68
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Bye.
